    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_978597861" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/978597861" />
    <a title="Muzzy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4285900-muzzy"><img alt="Muzzy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1390087632p2/4285900.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/978597861?book_show_action=true">Jun 26, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Muzzy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Muzzy" href="/user/show/4285900-muzzy">Muzzy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer978597861" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12888460820898281636">I wouldn‚Äôt recommend this book to any but the most specialized reader. You may want to take up this novel as a counterweight to Proust; otherwise I don‚Äôt think many people will enjoy reading it. Nor is it an important addition to the canon.<br/><br/>Which is not to say it‚Äôs a bad book. There are several dialogues here that are amazingly well written. And it‚Äôs a very fast, entertaining read ‚Äì at times I believed Gide took the words right out of my own head. <br/><br/>The character of Bernard, who runs away from home</span>
  <span id="freeText12888460820898281636" style="display:none">I wouldn‚Äôt recommend this book to any but the most specialized reader. You may want to take up this novel as a counterweight to Proust; otherwise I don‚Äôt think many people will enjoy reading it. Nor is it an important addition to the canon.<br /><br />Which is not to say it‚Äôs a bad book. There are several dialogues here that are amazingly well written. And it‚Äôs a very fast, entertaining read ‚Äì at times I believed Gide took the words right out of my own head. <br /><br />The character of Bernard, who runs away from home in the first chapter, is admirable and brave, but by the end he begins to speak in cliches, much of them warmed-over Nietzsche, and I felt that Gide was reaching for some kind of resolution. Another young man, Olivier, starts out fascinating, but remains two-dimensional, and we never really get to know him. With the exception of Olivier‚Äôs mother Pauline, the women in this story are typical victims from central casting. And what the hell is Alfred Jarry doing here? It‚Äôs a cheap cameo. I get the feeling Gide lacks the interest or the energy to develop his characters, to give them interiority. There‚Äôs just no complexity to them, and so the story ends up a thin, panoramic group portrait with no central focus, and no one to care about.<br /><br />All I can say for sure is that Counterfeiters is about young people, and their elders‚Äô attempts to keep them out of trouble and shape their moral education. Insofar as there could be a protagonist here, it‚Äôs Edouard, an unsuccessful novelist at work on a novel also called ‚ÄúThe Counterfeiters.‚Äù Though I don‚Äôt think he‚Äôs writing the same novel we‚Äôre reading, both Edouard and the narrator are concerned with his nephews and their relations.<br /><br />But that‚Äôs a gross simplification of a complicated plot with a dozen characters. Edouard doesn‚Äôt appear until chapter eight. Characters are introduced and then dropped. We don‚Äôt meet the quasi-villain until nearly the end. In this way Gide wanders, never fully committing. He tries to give us a world, including multiple perspectives, but with mixed results. In one important dialogue, Edouard delivers a beguiling theory of the novel:<br /><br />‚ÄúAs for me I should like not to cut at all. Please understand; I should like to put everything into my novel. I don‚Äôt want any cut of the scissors to limit its substance at one point rather than at another. For more than a year now that I have been working at it, nothing happens to me that I don‚Äôt put into it ‚Äì everything I see, everything I know, everything that other people‚Äôs lives and my own teach me . . .‚Äú<br /><br />That‚Äôs a fairly good description of the book we‚Äôre reading. It‚Äôs easy to assume that Edouard is a stand-in for Gide. But then, in the very next chapter, the narrator points out (rather obviously) that Edouard‚Äôs ideal is ridiculous:<br /><br />‚ÄúThe illogic of what he propounded was blatant, leaping painfully to the eye. It was clearly evident that Edouard‚Äôs skull housed two irreconcilable demands and that he was wearing himself out in his effort to harmonize them.‚Äù<br /><br />So which one is right? Who are we to believe? If Hamlet were to write a novel in French, it might look a lot like the Counterfeiters ‚Äì commit to nothing. Nothing is ever decided, not even after one young man commits suicide. The novel ends with Edouard thinking he‚Äôd like to get to know Caloub, a younger brother we haven‚Äôt heard from since the first chapter. And so the conflict between young and old goes on and on, with no resolution.<br /><br />By pretending to be an all-seeing camera that never discriminates, Gide tries in vain to protect his story from his readers. Yes, it‚Äôs a risk to uphold one character over another. The writer might make a bad choice, or we might disagree with him. But we cannot measure characters when their author won‚Äôt choose one for a hero. Ultimately, the lack of judgment is what dooms "the Counterfeiters."<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12888460820898281636" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


