    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4399885639" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4399885639" />
    <a title="Ken Ryu" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/70389522-ken-ryu"><img alt="Ken Ryu" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1606714837p2/70389522.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4399885639?book_show_action=true">Dec 20, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ken Ryu" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ken Ryu" href="/user/show/70389522-ken-ryu">Ken Ryu</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4399885639" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4099128645077376511">This is a complex book. Gide has three sets of stories that intersect but are not joined in a clean and simple fashion. He uses a diary reading as a narrative vehicle that allows the story to jump from one scene to the next. Besides the unusual narration form, the characters are purposefully difficult to distinguish. In the appendix of the book, Gide notes explain how he decides to leave the characters loosely defined by their appearance and manners. Instead the reader must juggle the different </span>
  <span id="freeText4099128645077376511" style="display:none">This is a complex book. Gide has three sets of stories that intersect but are not joined in a clean and simple fashion. He uses a diary reading as a narrative vehicle that allows the story to jump from one scene to the next. Besides the unusual narration form, the characters are purposefully difficult to distinguish. In the appendix of the book, Gide notes explain how he decides to leave the characters loosely defined by their appearance and manners. Instead the reader must juggle the different names, build a connection tree, and keep track of the various actions of each person. This is a task that I woefully failed. I was confused on who was whose brother and which character was romantically involved or interested in the next. <br /><br />The title points to false coins that some of the younger boys are passing around. Gide intends more from the title than just this literal aspect. The characters struggle to find purpose in life. Broken love, mistaken life choices, artistic struggles, and coming of age devastate most of the field. The devil and angels fight for their souls as the characters consider and often fail to discover truth.<br /><br />The interesting aspect of the novel is how well each chapter reads as a stand alone picture. The ending is surprising and gripping. The view to an almost shoplifting is vivid. The broken marriage and infidelities of a couple are stark and cold. Gide is a brilliant writer. His years of labor on this book show how he rejects simplistic approaches to the form and chooses to build a collage of stories and characters that challenge the reader. Perhaps the translation to English makes the form even more difficult, but his brilliance is felt if not fully comprehended.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4099128645077376511" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


